<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='480000' id='t-480000'>and Kiribati, along with 42 other nations in the world,</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='483000' id='t-483000'>will be under water within 50 to 100 years</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='485000' id='t-485000'>due to climate change</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='487000' id='t-487000'>and the associated sea-level rise from thermal expansion</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='490000' id='t-490000'>and the melting of freshwater into the ocean.</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='493000' id='t-493000'>The Islands rise only one to two meters</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='495000' id='t-495000'>above the surface.</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='497000' id='t-497000'>Some of the islands have already gone under water.</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='500000' id='t-500000'>And these nations are faced with a real problem.</span>
